Reasoning: The paper discusses the use of network analysis and computer-assisted analysis of scientific literature and patents to analyze the complexity of translating novel molecular entities and nanomaterials into pharmaceutical alternatives. This involves interdisciplinary communication and the organization and translation of biomedical knowledge, which are relevant to several sub-categories in computer science. Specifically, the use of network analysis and computer-assisted analysis of scientific literature and patents suggests relevance to information retrieval (cs.IR) and computational linguistics (cs.CL). The focus on interdisciplinary communication and the organization of knowledge suggests relevance to social and information networks (cs.SI) and digital libraries (cs.DL). Finally, the use of computer-assisted analysis of scientific literature and patents to analyze the complexity of drug design suggests relevance to cybernetics (cs.CY).
